        <!-- Two interview types -->
        <section id="interview-types" class="content-section">
          <h2>Two Types of Marriage Green Card Interviews</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">Which interview you attend depends on where you are in the process. Both test the same thing — that your marriage is genuine — but the logistics differ significantly.</p>

          <div class="interview-compare">
            <div class="interview-card aos">
              <span class="ic-label aos">Inside the U.S.</span>
              <h3>AOS Interview at USCIS</h3>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">Who attends:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">Both spouses together</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">Where:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">Local USCIS field office</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">When:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">After filing I-485 (Adjustment of Status)</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">Duration:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">30–60 minutes typical</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">What they check:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">Marriage validity, admissibility, I-485 petition accuracy</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">Outcome:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">Approved same day, RFE issued, or referred for further review</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">Common path:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">K-1 holders after marriage; spouses already in the U.S.</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="interview-card consular">
              <span class="ic-label consular">Abroad</span>
              <h3>Consular Interview for CR-1/IR-1</h3>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">Who attends:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">Foreign spouse only</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">Where:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">U.S. Embassy or Consulate abroad</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">When:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">After NVC processing; immigrant visa interview</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">Duration:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">15–30 minutes typical</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">What they check:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">Bona fide marriage, financial support, admissibility</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">Outcome:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">Visa approved, 221(g) hold, or refused</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ic-row">
                <span class="ic-row-label">Common path:</span>
                <span class="ic-row-val">Couples who married abroad; CR-1/IR-1 petitions</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="alert-box alert-info">
            <div class="alert-icon">💡</div>
            <div>
              <strong>AOS: Both spouses must attend and both may be questioned</strong>
              <p>Unlike the K-1 consular interview (foreign fiancé only), the AOS interview at USCIS brings both spouses into the room. The officer may question them jointly or separately. Some officers ask a few casual questions; others conduct a rigorous review. Go in prepared for a thorough interview regardless.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Category 1: How You Met & Relationship History -->
        <section id="how-you-met" class="content-section">
          <h2>Category 1 — How You Met &amp; Relationship History</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">Officers establish the foundation of your relationship here. They want a believable, consistent origin story with specific details — dates, platforms, circumstances — not vague summaries. Both spouses should be able to tell this story from their own perspective with matching core facts.</p>

          <div class="qa-category-label">How You Met</div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">How did you meet?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Be specific: name the platform (Hinge, Bumble, Facebook, through a mutual friend), give the approximate date or year, and describe what led to the first conversation. "We met online" is not enough — officers hear that constantly.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Who sent the first message or made the first move?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Either answer is fine. Officers are checking that both spouses tell the same story. If he messaged first, both of you should know that. If it was mutual, both accounts should reflect that.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">What was your first impression of your spouse?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">This is a personality question. A genuine, personal answer — even short — is far more convincing than "I thought they were nice." Officers notice when people light up talking about their partner.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">When did you first meet in person?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Give the month, year, and location. Explain who traveled to whom. This is one of the most important facts — it must match your petition documents and both spouses' passports.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Describe your first in-person meeting. Where did you go? What did you do?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Specific details here carry enormous weight. Name the city, a restaurant, an activity, a memorable moment from the visit. Generic answers suggest you weren't really there together.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">When did you know the relationship was serious?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Tell the honest story. It doesn't have to be a dramatic moment — "after the third time we talked, I knew this was different" is perfectly fine. Officers are listening for authenticity, not romance-novel perfection.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">When did you first say "I love you" to each other?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know the approximate timing — during a visit, over a video call. You don't need the exact date, but "sometime around our second visit, maybe six months in" is a much stronger answer than "I don't remember."</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">How many times have you visited each other in person?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know the exact number and the approximate dates of each visit. Being off by one visit, or giving very different counts than what's in the petition, raises questions. Both spouses should agree.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">How did you maintain the relationship long-distance?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Describe your communication routine: daily video calls, the apps you used (WhatsApp, FaceTime), text throughout the day, how you handled time zone differences. Paint a picture of an active, continuous relationship.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Have you had any difficulties or arguments in your relationship? How did you work through them?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Counterintuitively, "we've never had any problems" can seem less credible. Real couples navigate real challenges. Mentioning one disagreement and how you resolved it makes the relationship seem authentic.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-category-label">The Proposal</div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">How did you propose? Who proposed?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Officers ask this question very frequently and pay close attention to both spouses' answers. Know the date, the place, and the circumstances in vivid detail. Both spouses must be able to describe this consistently from their own perspective.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">When did you get engaged?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Give the month and year at minimum. If you have an engagement ring, know the rough details. This date should match anything submitted in your petition paperwork.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Did you tell your families about the engagement right away? How did they react?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">This reveals how integrated the relationship is in each person's family life. A genuine couple almost always involved their families. If reactions were complicated, honesty is better than pretending it was all positive.</div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Category 2: Daily Life & Living Situation -->
        <section id="daily-life" class="content-section">
          <h2>Category 2 — Daily Life &amp; Living Situation</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">These questions are the core of marriage fraud detection. An officer will ask intimate daily-life details that only two people who genuinely live together or spend significant time together would know. They look for specific, consistent answers from both spouses.</p>

          <div class="qa-category-label">Daily Routines</div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">What side of the bed does your spouse sleep on?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">This classic question is designed to verify that you have actually shared a bedroom. Know the answer without hesitation. Both spouses should agree — "his left, from his perspective" means something different from "the left side of the room."</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">What does your spouse typically eat for breakfast?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Officers love food questions. Know your spouse's breakfast habits — whether they skip it, what they usually have, if they have coffee or tea, what brand or type they prefer. Specific is convincing.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Who does the grocery shopping in your household?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know the honest answer. If you shop together on weekends but one person goes during the week, say so. An accurate description of your real routine is always better than a simplified version.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Who cooks? What does your spouse cook most often?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Name a specific dish your spouse makes regularly. "They make great pasta" is better than "they cook sometimes." If they don't cook, say so honestly.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">What time does your spouse wake up? Do they use an alarm?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Cohabiting couples know each other's sleep schedules. Even for couples who are still abroad, this question may come up if you have spent significant time together during visits.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Does your spouse have any habits or routines you find interesting or amusing?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">This open-ended question invites you to show that you genuinely know your partner as a person. A specific, affectionate answer here stands out and reinforces the legitimacy of the relationship.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">What does your spouse do on a typical weekend?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Describe their actual weekend activities — sleeping in, the gym, hiking, friends, cooking, watching sports. Know what they do when they're not at work.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-category-label">Home & Finances</div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Where do you currently live? Describe your home.</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know the city, state, and type of home (apartment, house). For AOS interviews where you already live together, know the floor layout, how many rooms, and basic details about each room. Both spouses must describe the same home consistently.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Do you rent or own? What is your monthly rent or mortgage?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know the financial basics of your household. If you've been living together, both spouses should know the rough rent or mortgage amount.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Do you have joint bank accounts? What bank do you use?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know whether you have joint accounts, the name of your bank, and roughly when you opened the account. Joint finances are strong evidence of a genuine marriage — if you have them, both spouses should know the details.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Do you own any property, cars, or other assets together?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">If yes, know the details. Shared assets are among the strongest evidence of a genuine marriage. Know the make and model of shared vehicles, the address of shared property.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Does your spouse have any pets?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">If they do, know the pet's name, type, and breed. This is the kind of specific personal detail that people in genuine relationships automatically know.</div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Category 3: Wedding & Family -->
        <section id="wedding-family" class="content-section">
          <h2>Category 3 — Wedding &amp; Family</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">Officers want to see that the wedding was real, planned, and witnessed — and that both families are aware of and involved in the marriage. Thin or evasive answers about the wedding itself are a significant red flag.</p>

          <div class="qa-category-label">The Wedding</div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Where did you get married? What was the venue?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Name the city, state, and the specific venue — courthouse, church, restaurant, outdoor garden, family home. Both spouses must give the same answer.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">What was the date of your wedding?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know your own wedding date precisely. This is on your marriage certificate — which you brought to the interview. Getting your wedding date wrong is one of the most flagrant red flags possible.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Who officiated the wedding?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know whether it was a justice of the peace, a judge, a religious officiant, or someone with an online ordination. Know their name if possible.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Who attended the wedding? Describe the guest list.</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know who was present. For a small courthouse wedding, name everyone. For a larger ceremony, give a general count and name the key people — immediate family, closest friends. Both spouses should know this.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Describe your wedding day. What happened?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Walk through the day: where you got ready, when you arrived at the venue, how the ceremony went, whether you had a reception or dinner afterward. The more vivid and specific this narrative is, the more convincing.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Did you have a honeymoon? Where did you go?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">If yes, know the destination, rough dates, and what you did. If you haven't had one yet, say so and explain why (finances, timing, waiting for the green card).</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">What did your spouse wear at the wedding?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Another vivid-detail question. Know what your spouse wore — even a basic description is sufficient. You should have photos to back this up.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Did you exchange rings? Do you wear your wedding ring?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">If you wear rings, you should be wearing them to the interview. Know when you got the rings, where they were purchased (even approximately), and whether they were exchanged at the ceremony.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-category-label">Family</div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">What are your spouse's parents' names? Are they alive?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know both parents' first names at minimum. Know whether the parents are still alive, and if not, when they passed. Know whether the parents are married, divorced, or remarried.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Have you met your spouse's family? Do they know about the marriage?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">If you've met them, describe how — in person during a visit, at the wedding, or via video call. The family being aware of and supportive of the marriage strongly supports the marriage's legitimacy.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Do you want children? Does your spouse want children?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Any honest answer is fine. Officers are checking that you have had these conversations and that both spouses have consistent, considered responses — not that you agree on a specific number.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Does your spouse have children from a previous relationship?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">If yes, know the children's names and approximate ages. This information was submitted on the petition and must match your answer.</div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Category 4: Future Plans -->
        <section id="future-plans" class="content-section">
          <h2>Category 4 — Future Plans</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">Officers confirm that the couple has a real, shared plan for their life together in the United States. Vague or contradictory answers about where you'll live, how you'll support yourselves, and what you intend to build together raise doubts about genuine intent.</p>

          <div class="qa-category-label">Living Arrangements</div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Where do you plan to live? Have you decided on a city?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know the city and state. If you are already living together, describe the current situation and whether you plan to stay. If moving, explain where and roughly when. The address should be consistent with what's on the petition.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Will you be living with other people — family members, roommates?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Answer honestly. Temporarily living with family while you get settled is common and not a red flag. Officers are checking for any situation that suggests the couple won't actually be cohabitating as spouses.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Do you have a lease or mortgage? When does it expire?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know your current housing situation's terms. If you have a lease, know the approximate expiration date. This shows that the living arrangement is real and ongoing.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-category-label">Career & Finances</div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">What does your spouse do for work? Who is their employer?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Know the company name, your spouse's job title, and how long they've been there. Know roughly what they do day-to-day. This is a basic fact any genuine spouse would know.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">What are your career plans in the United States?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">You can work legally after marriage and adjustment of status. Describe your profession, relevant skills, and general direction — whether you plan to look for work in your field, consider further education, or stay home initially to manage the household. Any honest answer is valid.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">How will you financially support yourselves as a couple?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Describe the household income plan: your spouse's current employment, your expected future earnings, any other income sources. Officers are not expecting a detailed financial plan — just a reasonable, realistic overview.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-category-label">Long-Term Plans</div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Do you plan to stay in the United States permanently?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Answer honestly. Most couples intend to stay; say so. If you have plans to eventually return to the home country together, that's worth explaining briefly. The green card indicates intent to reside permanently, so this should be consistent with your application.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Do you have family or friends in both countries you'd like to visit?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">Having family ties abroad is normal and does not hurt your case. Mentioning that you plan to visit the other country occasionally shows a realistic, integrated life plan.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-card">
            <div class="qa-q">Have you discussed where you see yourselves in five years?</div>
            <div class="qa-hint">This open-ended question invites you to demonstrate that you are genuine life partners who think about the future together. A thoughtful, specific answer — mentioning career goals, possibly owning a home, family plans — is far more convincing than a generic "we just want to be happy."</div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Stokes Interview -->
        <section id="stokes" class="content-section">
          <h2>The Stokes Interview — What It Is &amp; How to Prepare</h2>

          <div class="stokes-box">
            <span class="stokes-badge">Important — Separate Rooms Interview</span>
            <h3>What is a Stokes interview?</h3>
            <p>A Stokes interview (named after the 1986 court case <em>Matter of Stokes</em>) is a separate-rooms interview where USCIS questions each spouse independently and then compares the answers. You and your spouse are placed in different rooms simultaneously. The officer asks each of you the same set of questions, records both sets of answers, and then compares them for consistency.</p>
            <p>A Stokes interview is not an accusation of fraud — it is a tool officers use when they have concerns about a marriage's legitimacy or simply when their office's standard practice requires it. The officer can request one at any point during the AOS interview process, sometimes even scheduling a second appointment for the Stokes specifically.</p>
            <p>The good news: real couples almost always have some discrepancies on minor details. Officers expect this. What triggers a denial is major factual contradictions — completely different accounts of how you met, wrong wedding dates, mismatched accounts of cohabitation.</p>

            <div class="stokes-tips">
              <div class="stokes-tip">
                <strong>Study your shared facts together</strong>
                Go through all major dates, addresses, family names, and key events as a couple and make sure you're aligned.
              </div>
              <div class="stokes-tip">
                <strong>Don't over-script</strong>
                Scripted identical answers actually raise suspicion. Natural recall from real memory is what officers look for.
              </div>
              <div class="stokes-tip">
                <strong>Stay calm if surprised</strong>
                If you get an unexpected question, take a breath and answer from your genuine memory. "I don't remember the exact detail" is honest and acceptable.
              </div>
              <div class="stokes-tip">
                <strong>Discrepancies are not automatic denial</strong>
                After the interviews, you will be given an opportunity to explain any discrepancies together. Officers expect some variation — genuine couples do not have synchronized memories.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Mid-page CTA -->
        <div class="cta-mid">
          <div class="cta-mid-text">
            <h3>Worried about a Stokes interview?</h3>
            <p>An experienced immigration attorney can do a mock interview with you — asking the actual questions officers use, identifying inconsistencies before the real thing, and coaching both spouses on how to handle separate questioning.</p>
