        </div>

        <!-- Red Flags -->
        <section id="red-flags" class="content-section">
          <h2>Red Flags That Trigger Harder Questioning</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">Certain patterns alert officers to look more closely. None of these are automatic denials, but each one tends to lead to more detailed questioning and sometimes a Stokes interview request.</p>

          <div class="red-flags-list">
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">⚡</div>
              <div>
                <div class="rf-title">Very short marriage before filing</div>
                <div class="rf-desc">Filing for AOS within weeks of the wedding, especially without shared documentation, raises the question of whether the marriage was entered for immigration benefit rather than genuine union. Officers will ask detailed relationship history questions to establish a pre-wedding relationship foundation.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">⚡</div>
              <div>
                <div class="rf-title">Significant age gap</div>
                <div class="rf-desc">A large age difference between spouses (15+ years) is not disqualifying, but it tends to attract closer scrutiny. Officers will ask more detailed questions about how the couple met and what drew them together. Strong relationship evidence and natural, specific answers carry extra weight here.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">⚡</div>
              <div>
                <div class="rf-title">No shared language</div>
                <div class="rf-desc">If spouses do not share a common language and no interpreter was present during the marriage ceremony, officers will probe how the couple communicates and how the relationship developed. Be ready to explain your communication methods in detail.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">⚡</div>
              <div>
                <div class="rf-title">Thin or sparse evidence of the relationship</div>
                <div class="rf-desc">Arriving at an interview with very few photos, no communication records, and no joint financial documents signals that the relationship may not have the typical footprint of a genuine marriage. Come with organized, substantive evidence across multiple categories.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">⚡</div>
              <div>
                <div class="rf-title">Prior visa overstay or immigration violations</div>
                <div class="rf-desc">If the foreign spouse has a history of overstaying a prior visa, officers will scrutinize the marriage more carefully to ensure it is not a means to regularize status after a violation. Be prepared to address this directly if it applies.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">⚡</div>
              <div>
                <div class="rf-title">Multiple prior immigrant visa petitions</div>
                <div class="rf-desc">If the U.S. citizen spouse has petitioned for prior immigrants who were denied or withdrew, or if they were previously found to have participated in a fraudulent marriage, this is a serious flag. Officers have access to full petition history.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">⚡</div>
              <div>
                <div class="rf-title">Spouses who can't describe each other's basic facts</div>
                <div class="rf-desc">If one spouse cannot name the other's employer, doesn't know their date of birth, or is vague about basic shared history, the interview will escalate quickly. These facts should be second nature.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="red-flag-item">
              <div class="rf-icon">⚡</div>
              <div>
                <div class="rf-title">Inconsistencies between petition paperwork and interview answers</div>
                <div class="rf-desc">Officers compare everything you say in the interview against what was submitted in writing. If the petition says you met in March 2023 but you say it was 2024, that contradiction is immediately visible. Review your petition carefully before the interview.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Evidence to Bring -->
        <section id="evidence" class="content-section">
          <h2>Evidence to Bring to the Interview</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">Your evidence package tells the story of your marriage visually and documentarily. Organize everything in a labeled tabbed folder or binder. Officers should be able to see what you have and find any specific item within seconds.</p>

          <div class="evidence-grid">
            <div class="evidence-cat">
              <h3>Required Documents</h3>
              <ul class="evidence-list">
                <li>USCIS interview appointment notice (AOS) or DS-260 confirmation (consular)</li>
                <li>Both spouses' valid passports (AOS); foreign spouse passport (consular)</li>
                <li>Certified marriage certificate</li>
                <li>Birth certificates for both spouses</li>
                <li>I-797 petition approval notice</li>
                <li>Completed I-485 and I-130 copies (AOS) or immigrant visa application copies (consular)</li>
                <li>Medical exam sealed envelope — do not open (consular)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="evidence-cat">
              <h3>Relationship History</h3>
              <ul class="evidence-list">
                <li>40–60 printed photos organized chronologically — different dates, locations, contexts</li>
                <li>Engagement photos with date and location metadata</li>
                <li>Wedding photos and any ceremony documentation</li>
                <li>Flight tickets and hotel receipts from visits to each other</li>
                <li>Passport entry/exit stamps matching visit dates</li>
                <li>2–3 support letters from people who know the couple well</li>
                <li>Communication logs — WhatsApp chat exports, call history screenshots</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="evidence-cat">
              <h3>Joint Financial Evidence</h3>
              <ul class="evidence-list">
                <li>Joint bank account statements (3–6 months)</li>
                <li>Most recent joint or co-filed tax return</li>
                <li>Joint credit card statements (if any)</li>
                <li>Lease or mortgage in both names</li>
                <li>Life insurance naming spouse as beneficiary</li>
                <li>Utility bills listing both names at the same address</li>
                <li>I-864 Affidavit of Support with supporting financial documents</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="evidence-cat">
              <h3>Legal & Background Documents</h3>
              <ul class="evidence-list">
                <li>Divorce decree(s) for any prior marriages — both spouses</li>
                <li>Death certificate if widowed</li>
                <li>Police clearance certificates (if required)</li>
                <li>Court disposition documents for any criminal history</li>
                <li>Certified translations for all non-English documents</li>
                <li>Prior visa stamps and travel documentation</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="alert-box alert-success">
            <div class="alert-icon">✓</div>
            <div>
              <strong>The "bona fide marriage" standard is what you are proving</strong>
              <p>USCIS uses a totality of the evidence test — no single document proves or disproves a marriage. Photos alone are not enough. Tax returns alone are not enough. The strongest applications have evidence across all four categories above, showing a relationship that exists across time, distance, finances, and family life. See our full <SmartLink href="/bona-fide-marriage">bona fide marriage evidence guide</SmartLink> and the <SmartLink href="/4-pillars-of-evidence-partner-visa">4 pillars of evidence framework</SmartLink>.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Day-of Tips -->
        <section id="day-of-tips" class="content-section">
          <h2>Day-Of Interview Tips</h2>

          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">1</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Arrive early</strong>
                <p>Plan to arrive at the USCIS office or embassy at least 30–45 minutes before your appointment. Security lines can be long. Being late can result in losing your slot and waiting months for another appointment.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">2</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Dress professionally</strong>
                <p>Business casual or business formal for both spouses. First impressions matter. Dressing well signals that you take the process seriously — and officers notice. Both spouses should dress to the same level.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">3</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Bring organized, complete documents</strong>
                <p>Use a labeled tabbed binder. Officers notice when applicants can produce any document in seconds versus fumbling through a disorganized pile. Organization signals preparation and seriousness.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">4</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Answer only what's asked — don't over-explain</strong>
                <p>Give direct, complete answers. Do not volunteer additional information beyond what the question requires. Over-explaining introduces inconsistencies and raises follow-up questions you haven't prepared for.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">5</div>
              <div>
                <strong>It's okay to say "I don't know" or "I'd have to check"</strong>
                <p>It is far better to admit you don't remember an exact detail than to guess and give a wrong answer that contradicts the petition. "I'd have to look at my records for the exact date" is an honest, reasonable answer officers accept.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">6</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Stay calm — nervousness is expected</strong>
                <p>Officers know people are nervous in immigration interviews. Do not let anxiety make you appear evasive. Breathe, maintain reasonable eye contact, and take a moment to collect your thoughts before answering. Calm, direct answers build confidence.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">7</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Do not bring notes or cheat sheets</strong>
                <p>Consulting a prepared list of answers tells the officer your answers are scripted rather than genuine. All relationship knowledge should come from your actual shared experience. You may bring documents for reference, but not relationship fact sheets.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-item">
              <div class="tip-num">8</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Wear your wedding rings</strong>
                <p>If you exchanged wedding rings, wear them to the interview. Officers sometimes notice whether married couples are wearing rings. This is a small detail, but small details add up in an officer's overall impression.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- What happens if answers don't match -->
        <section id="answer-mismatch" class="content-section">
          <h2>What Happens If Our Answers Don't Match?</h2>

          <div class="mismatch-box">
            <h3>Don't panic — minor discrepancies are completely normal</h3>
            <p>Genuine couples do not have synchronized, identical memories. Officers expect variation on minor details: the exact restaurant where you had your first date, the precise color of your spouse's shirt at the wedding, the exact day of the week you had a specific conversation. These minor inconsistencies do not indicate fraud — they indicate that you are human.</p>
            <p>What officers flag are major factual contradictions: completely different accounts of how you met, wrong wedding dates, conflicting stories about living arrangements, mismatched descriptions of your home's layout. These suggest the spouses are not actually living as a married couple.</p>
            <p>If the officer identifies a discrepancy during the Stokes comparison, you will typically be brought back together to explain. Remain calm, speak to each other naturally, and explain why the accounts differ. A reasonable, honest explanation — "I think we remember it differently, but I know for certain it was..." — is far better than defensive or evasive responses.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
            <div class="alert-icon">⚠️</div>
            <div>
              <strong>When discrepancies are significant — do not make things worse</strong>
              <p>If you realize mid-interview that you have given an answer that contradicts your petition paperwork, do not try to cover it up or change the story further. Acknowledge the discrepancy, offer a simple explanation ("I think I confused the date — the certificate shows it was March"), and let the officer decide. Doubling down on a wrong answer compounds the problem significantly.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- After the interview: outcomes -->
        <section id="outcomes" class="content-section">
          <h2>After the Interview: Possible Outcomes</h2>

          <div class="outcome-grid">
            <div class="outcome-card approved">
              <div class="outcome-icon">✅</div>
              <h3>Approved Same Day</h3>
              <p><strong>Most common outcome</strong> for well-prepared couples with solid evidence. The officer is satisfied the marriage is bona fide and the applicant is admissible.</p>
              <p>For AOS: the officer stamps the passport and the green card is mailed within 2–3 weeks. For CR-1: your passport is collected for visa stamp, returned in a few days.</p>
              <div class="outcome-badge badge-green">Green card on the way</div>
            </div>

            <div class="outcome-card mail">
              <div class="outcome-icon">📬</div>
              <h3>Approved — Decision by Mail</h3>
              <p>Some USCIS offices don't make decisions on the spot. The officer indicates the interview went well but the official approval notice will be mailed.</p>
              <p>This is not a bad sign — it often means the case is solid but the officer follows a standard process of sending written decisions.</p>
              <div class="outcome-badge badge-blue">Expect notice within weeks</div>
            </div>

            <div class="outcome-card rfe">
              <div class="outcome-icon">📋</div>
              <h3>Request for Evidence (RFE)</h3>
              <p>The officer needs more documentation — typically more relationship evidence, additional financial records, or clarification on something raised in the interview.</p>
              <p>An RFE is not a denial. Respond thoroughly and within the deadline (usually 87 days). An immigration attorney can help you put together the strongest possible RFE response.</p>
              <div class="outcome-badge badge-yellow">Action required — respond promptly</div>
            </div>

            <div class="outcome-card denied">
              <div class="outcome-icon">🚫</div>
              <h3>Denied</h3>
              <p>True interview-stage denials are rare for couples with genuine marriages. They happen when the officer finds the marriage fraudulent, discovers an inadmissibility ground, or identifies serious petition problems.</p>
              <p>If denied, you receive a written notice with the specific reason. Consult an immigration attorney immediately to evaluate appeal, waiver, or refiling options.</p>
              <div class="outcome-badge badge-red">Consult an attorney immediately</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- FAQs -->
        <section id="faq" class="content-section">
          <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
          <div class="faq-list">
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Do both spouses attend the marriage green card interview?</summary>
              <p>For an Adjustment of Status (AOS) interview at a USCIS local office, both spouses must attend together. For a CR-1 consular interview at a U.S. embassy abroad, only the foreign spouse attends — the U.S. citizen does not go to the embassy. In both cases, the interviewing officer may ask each spouse questions separately to compare answers.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What is a Stokes interview and why does it happen?</summary>
              <p>A Stokes interview is a separate-rooms interview where USCIS questions each spouse independently and compares answers. It typically happens when an officer has concerns about the marriage — red flags like a very short marriage before filing, large age gaps, no shared language, or thin evidence. Real couples almost always have some discrepancies on minor details; what matters is consistency on major facts. If selected for a Stokes, remain calm and answer honestly from your genuine memory.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What happens if our answers don't match at the interview?</summary>
              <p>Minor discrepancies on small details are completely normal — genuine couples don't have memorized identical answers for every question. Officers expect some variation. If an answer diverges, calmly explain: "We may remember it differently. What I recall is..." The concern is major factual contradictions — wrong spouse's birthday, completely different accounts of how you met, mismatched addresses. Those trigger follow-up. Small differences on minor details do not.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>How long does the marriage green card interview take?</summary>
              <p>Standard AOS interviews at USCIS typically last 30–60 minutes. Consular CR-1 interviews are often shorter, around 15–30 minutes. If the officer has questions or concerns, the interview can run longer. A Stokes separate-rooms interview may take 1–2 hours total since both spouses are questioned independently and answers are compared.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What documents should I bring to the marriage green card interview?</summary>
              <p>For an AOS interview: your USCIS appointment notice, both spouses' passports, your marriage certificate, joint financial documents (bank statements, tax returns, lease), photos together, any prior divorce decrees, and copies of the I-485, I-130, and I-864 petitions. For a CR-1 consular interview: passport, DS-260 confirmation, I-797 approval notice, sealed medical exam envelope, birth certificate, marriage certificate, financial documents, and relationship evidence. Organize everything in a labeled tabbed folder.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Can a marriage green card be denied at the interview?</summary>
              <p>Yes, though outright denials at the interview are not the most common outcome. More frequently, an officer will issue a Request for Evidence (RFE) asking for more proof of the marriage's legitimacy, or place the case in administrative processing. Actual denials happen when the officer finds the marriage fraudulent, a spouse is inadmissible for another reason, or there are serious inconsistencies. Consulting an immigration attorney before the interview significantly reduces the risk of a denial.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </section>

